Project 4¶

The purpose of this project is to visualize a longitude and latidude dataset with maps.

Specifically, you will find an interactive map showing all Walmart locations, and their type (Store, SuperCenter, or Distribution Center) as of August 2006.

SuperCenters can have special additions that normal Walmart stores do not have, such as: Tire & Lube Express, Pet shops, Garden centres, Optical centres, Pharmacies, One-hour photo processing labs, Alcove shops including hair and nail salons, cellular phone stores, local bank branches, video rental stores, and fast food outlets, and Portrait studios.

To find out more about the differences between types of Walmarts: Difference Between Walmart and Walmart Supercenter | Difference Between http://www.differencebetween.net/business/difference-between-walmart-and-walmart-supercenter/#ixzz7SLpSG4hf

import folium
import pandas as pd

Part 1: Data Gathering¶

Below, I gather the list of all Walmart (as of 08/2006) locations from a public csv on github. Then, I read it into a pandas dataframe. Then I check to see if it has any missing data values.

In [2]:
#grab the csv
wm_csv = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kosukeimai/qss/master/DISCOVERY/walmart.csv"
wm_table = pd.read_csv(wm_csv)

#check for missing values in the same manner as the project description
long_count = wm_table[pd.notnull(wm_table["long"])]["long"].count()
lat_count = wm_table[pd.notnull(wm_table["lat"])]["lat"].count()
type_count = wm_table[pd.notnull(wm_table["type"])]["type"].count()
print("Number of McDonald's entries:", len(wm_table), "\nNumber of longitude entries:", long_count,  "\nNumber of latitude entries:", lat_count, "\nNumber of Store Types:", type_count, "\nNo missing entries")

Part 2: Creating an Empty Map¶

Below I create an empty map using folium in the same manner as the project description. I set the zoom to further out so a larger sample of Walmarts are visible.

In [3]:
wm_map_osm = folium.Map(location=[39.29, -76.61], zoom_start=10)
#wm_map_osm

Part 3: Combining the Walmart Locations with the Empty Map¶

Below, I add markers to the map to display Walmart locations. The Super Centers (which have extra sections, such as groceries) are shown in red, while the normal are shown in blue, and distribution centers are shown in green. I also prove that there are only 3 types of Walmarts, as to not look over any in the ending else-clause.

If you are having performance issues with the map, please zoom in, and it will increase performance and slow down the lagginess.

In [5]:
for index, walmart in wm_table.iterrows():
    if walmart['type'] == 'SuperCenter':
        folium.Marker(location=[walmart['lat'], walmart['long']],
                    icon=folium.Icon(color='red')).add_to(wm_map_osm)
      
    elif walmart['type'] == 'DistributionCenter':
        folium.Marker(location=[walmart['lat'], walmart['long']],
                    icon=folium.Icon(color='green')).add_to(wm_map_osm)
        
    else:
        folium.Marker(location=[walmart['lat'], walmart['long']],
                    icon=folium.Icon(color='blue')).add_to(wm_map_osm)
        
wm_map_osm

Make this Notebook Trusted to load map: File -> Trust Notebook

As you can see from the map, by 2006, heavy city areas (such as mainlad Maryland) had lots of Walmart Stores, but no Walmart Supercenters. This is probably due to the fact that other existing grocery stores, auto shops, and the like were too prominent for people to go to Walmart for those services. However, if you direct your attention to the Eastern Shore of MD and even Delaware, there are far fewer Walmarts, and the majority of them are SuperCenters. This is because of the smaller populations, and even in proportionally larger cities (i.e. Salisbury), Walmart can beat out competitors in the grocery and auto shop areas.
